{{Infobox television | show_name = K-Town | image = | caption = | genre = [[Reality television|Reality]] | creator = | developer = | writer = | director = Eugene Choi, Eddie Kim, and [[Mike Le]] | creative_director = Eugene Choi, Eddie Kim, and [[Mike Le]] | starring = Cammy Chung, Christine Chang, Jasmine Chang, Joe Cha, Jowe Lee, Scarlet Chan, Steve Kim, Violet Kim, Young Lee, So Young Park | theme_music_composer = | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = United States | language = English | num_seasons = 2 | num_episodes = 17 | list_episodes = | executive_producer = [[Tyrese Gibson]], Eugene Choi, Eddie Kim, [[Mike Le]], Evan Bregman, [[Tony DiSanto]], [[Liz Gateley]], Benjamin Silverman | producer = Jerry Chan, Morrow Pettigrew | editor = Jerry Chan, Peter Samet | location = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] | cinematography = Ray Huang, Aaron Torres, Jon Peter | camera = Ray Huang, Aaron Torres, Jon Peter, Kacper Skowron | runtime = about 22 minutes per episode | company = Electus, HQ Pictures | distributor = [[YouTube]] | channel = LOUD | picture_format = | audio_format = | first_run = | first_aired = July 11, 2012 | last_aired = January 9, 2013 | preceded_by = | followed_by = ''Roll Models'' | related = | website = https://www.youtube.com/loud | website_title = https://www.facebook.com/ktownrealityshow | production_website = http://ktownlosangeles.blogspot.com/ }}
'''''K-Town''''' is an American [[reality television]] series about the lives of a group of young Asian Americans living in Los Angeles' [[Koreatown, Los Angeles|Koreatown]]. The cast is mostly of Korean descent, with the exception of Scarlet Chan (who is of Chinese descent).<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|title=Tough Times for Tiger Moms as Asian-America Meets 'Jersey Shore'|author=[[Jeff Yang]]|date=2012-07-17|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/07/17/tough-times-for-tiger-moms-as-asian-america-meets-jersey-shore/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[Curbed]]|date=2012-05-22|author=Adrian Glick Kudler|title=Preview the K-Town Reality Show Premiering This Summer|url=http://la.curbed.com/archives/2012/05/preview_the_ktown_reality_show_premiering_this_summer.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jezebel.com/5926910/asian+american-jersey-shore-finally-airs--but-not-on-tv|work=[[Jezebel.com]]|title=Asian-American Jersey Shore Finally Airs — But Not on TV|author=Doug Berry}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamag.com/laculture/culturefilesblog/2012/11/27/ktown-debuts-second-season-cue-rejoicing-and-moans|author=Michelle No|work=[[Los Angeles Magazine]]|title=K-Town Debuts Second Season Cue Rejoicing And Moans|date=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sfweekly.com/exhibitionist/2012/07/k-town_episode_1_recap.php|work=[[SFWeekly]]|date=2012-07-16|author=Sylvie Kim|title="Korean Jersey Shore" Finally Debuts ... Straight to YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/k-town-reality-show-episode-1-youtube_n_1683550.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|title='K-Town' Reality Show: Korean-American 'Jersey Shore' Hits YouTube|date=2012-07-18}}</ref> The show ran for two seasons.
The series is directed by Eugene Choi, Eddie Kim and [[Mike Le]], produced by Choi, Kim, Le as well as [[Tyrese Gibson]] and Jerry Chan, edited by Jerry Chan, with cinematography from Ray Huang, Aaron Torres and Jon Peter.
The series originally casted Jennifer Field and Peter Le, a known webcam personality which was reported by the press initially but was replaced by Jowe Lee and Cammie Chung before the show aired.
