'''Michael Green''' is an [[United States|American]] [[talent manager]], [[entrepreneur]] and [[movie producer]].<ref name=forbes>Pomerantz, Dorothy. [https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2001/1210/046.html Dog-and-Pony Show]. ''Forbes''. December 10, 2001.</ref>
==Career== Green began his career as a personal appearance agent in the early 90's at Irvin Arthur Associates representing stand up comedians. He then moved to talent management at Gallin-Morey Associates, where he eventually became a Senior Manager.<ref name=bio>[http://www.thecollective-la.com/about-us/partners/michael-green/ Partners: Michael Green]. ''The Collective''.</ref>
In 1997, he co-founded [[The Firm, Inc.|The Firm]], a music and talent management agency, with [[Jeff Kwatinetz]].<ref>[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/106/106232.html The Firm Company Profile]. ''Yahoo! Finance''.</ref> The company grew rapidly, eventually managing [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Korn]], [[Limp Bizkit]], [[Pamela Anderson]] and others. The Firm’s clients were responsible for more than $1.5 billion in business and the business was valued at more than $250 million.<ref name=forbes/> Expanding beyond the representation business, The Firm also acquired and sold the shoe brand [[Pony International|Pony]], and controlled an equity position in [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]]s.<ref name=forbes/><ref>Lieberman, Allyson. [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/69072486.html?dids=69072486:69072486&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+27%2C+2001&author=Allyson+Lieberman&pub=New+York+Post&desc=TAKING+A+RIDE+ON+PONY+-+FIRM+AIMS+TO+BRING+BACK+SNEAKER+BRAND&pqatl=google Taking a Ride on Pony - Firm Aims to Bring Back Sneaker Brand]. ''The New York Post''. February 27, 2001.</ref> In 2002, Green sold his interests in the company to spend time with his family.<ref name=bio/>
In 2005, he founded a new management company, The Collective.<ref>Donahue, Ann. [https://books.google.com/books?id=DhMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=Michael+Green+The+Collective&source=bl&ots=Vg5fi24ACw&sig=yOTa0yguCRXT2_tTFTliRTY5bWs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zb1iT7aEHvC42QWR37TqCA&ved=0CHEQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Michael%20Green%20The%20Collective&f=false 'Mad' Men]. ''Billboard''. June 14, 2008.</ref> The Collective continued to represent Green’s longtime clients like [[Martin Lawrence]], and also signed [[Linkin Park]], [[Counting Crows]], [[Enrique Iglesias]], [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Alanis Morissette]], and [[Emile Hirsch]], among others.<ref name=digi>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/pr/273121#ixzz1pIKhW5OP Hey Apple... Knife! Annoying Orange Kitchen Carnage Slices Through the App Store]. ''Digital Journal''.</ref><ref>Mitchell, Gail. [http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/legal-and-management/exclusive-godsmack-counting-crows-sign-with-1005056912.story Exclusive: Godsmack, Counting Crows Sign With the Collective]. ''Billboard''. March 3, 2011.</ref> As CEO, Green expanded The Collective outside simple talent management, acquiring the horror movie site [[Bloody-Disgusting.com]] and popular YouTube accounts and personalities like [[Fred Figglehorn|Fred]] and [[Annoying Orange]] under [[Collective Digital Studio]].<ref name=digi/><ref>Graser, Marc. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117971910?refCatId=1009 Collective nabs Bloody-Disgusting]. ''Variety''. September 12, 2007.</ref>
