'''''Pinball FX 2''''' (stylized as '''''Pinball FX2''''') is a [[pinball]] [[video game]] for [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], and [[Microsoft Windows]] ([[Windows XP|XP]] and higher)<ref name="steam">{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/226980/?snr=1_7_15__13|publisher=Valve Software|title=Pinball FX2}}</ref> and is the sequel to ''[[Pinball FX]]''. It was developed by [[Zen Studios]] and published by [[Microsoft Studios (game studio)|Microsoft Studios]]. It was released on October 27, 2010 via the [[Xbox Live Arcade]] service. The game includes several new features, such as local multiplayer and the ability to tweak table settings. Players can also import all of the tables from ''Pinball FX'' they had previously purchased. The Windows 8 version of ''Pinball FX 2'' was released on the [[Windows Store]] on October 27, 2012, two years after the original XBLA release.<ref name="win8">{{cite web|last=Mallory|first=Jordan|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/10/27/pinball-fx-2-ricochets-onto-windows-8/|title=Pinball FX 2 ricochets onto Windows 8|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=October 28, 2012|date=October 27, 2012}}</ref> The game was subsequently released for other Windows platforms via [[Steam (software)|Steam]] on May 10, 2013.<ref name="steam"/>  ''Pinball FX 2'' was announced for [[Windows Phone]] in February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpcentral.com/pinball-fx-2-carcassonne-and-more-xbox-live-games-coming-windows-phone|title=Pinball FX2, Carcassonne, and more Xbox Live games coming to Windows Phone|date=22 February 2012|publisher=|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>

==Gameplay==
[[Image:Pinballfx2 table.png|thumb|left|The ''Pasha'' table as it appears in the Xbox 360 version. ''Pinball FX 2'' is available with either time limited trials of all tables on Xbox platforms and Steam or full play with video advertisements for non-''Star Wars'' tables on the current Windows 8 version, with the ability to unlock full tables via [[downloadable content]].]]

''Pinball FX 2'' uses the same basic rules as a physical [[pinball]] machine, but in a virtual environment.  As with a traditional pinball machine, the player fires a steel ball onto the [[Pinball#Machine layout|playfield]] using a plunger.  Once the ball is in play the player controls the [[Pinball#Flippers|flippers]] and can [[Pinball#Nudging|nudge]] the machine to influence the path of the ball.<ref name="the game">{{cite video game|title=Pinball FX 2|developer=Zen Studios|publisher=Microsoft Studios|date=2008-10-27}}</ref> Each of the game's tables become more complex as the game advances, opening new paths and opportunities.<ref name="the game" />

The game allows use of the [[Xbox Live Vision]] camera to operate the flippers and to video chat with [[Xbox Live]] opponents.<ref name="gamezone review">{{Cite web |url=http://xbox.gamezone.com/reviews/item/pinball_fx_2_review/ |title=Pinball FX 2 review |first=B. |last=James |publisher=GameZone |accessdate=2010-11-30 |date=2010-11-03}}</ref> It also features [[ladder tournament|leaderboards]] and online multiplayer for up to four players. Players can also participate in [[Split screen (computer graphics)|split-screen]] multiplayer.<ref name="gamezone review" />  Multiplayer games are won by being the first to achieve the set high score, which can be adjusted from 10 to 100 million points. Penalties can also be set for losing a ball with players losing anywhere from 5 to 25 percent of their score when a ball is lost.<ref name="the game" />

===Tables===
{{See also|Pinball FX#Tables|l1=Tables for Pinball FX}}
''Pinball FX 2'' is available free of charge and includes tables that can be played with a set time limit (Xbox and Steam) or fully with video advertisements (Windows 8). Players can choose to download an expansion pack dubbed ''Pinball FX 2 Core'' which unlocks four tables: BioLab,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/09/24/biolab-table-revealed-for-pinball-fx-2/ |publisher=[[Joystiq]] |accessdate=2010-11-29 |title=BioLab table revealed for Pinball FX 2 |first=Justin |last=McElroy |date=2010-09-24}}</ref> Pasha,<ref name="destructoid review">{{Cite web |url=http://beta.destructoid.com/review-pinball-fx-2 |title=Review: Pinball FX 2 |date=2010-10-30 |first=Nick |last=Chester |publisher=Destructoid |accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref> Rome,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5638806/pinball-fx-2s-rome-table-likely-not-built-in-a-day/gallery/ |title=Pinball FX 2's Rome Table Likely Not Built In A Day |first=Mike |last=Fahey |publisher=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=2010-11-29 |date=2010-09-15}}</ref> and Secrets of the Deep.<ref name="destructoid review" />  Additional tables can be purchased individually, or via compilations.  The first compilation, titled ''Pinball FX Classic'', contains four tables from the original ''Pinball FX''.<ref name="mvcuk">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/press-releases/63527/Pinball-FX-2 |title=Taking Care of Business: Pinball FX 2 Pricing Explained & Secrets of the Deep Revealed |date=2010-09-29 |accessdate=2010-11-30 |publisher=mcvuk.com}}</ref> As the original ''Pinball FX'' was delisted from Xbox Live Marketplace, people who purchased ''Pinball FX'' receive the Classic collection, as well as other tables they purchased for that title, for free. The second compilation, ''[[Marvel Pinball]]'', has four pinball tables based on major Marvel Comics characters: [[Blade (comics)|Blade]], [[Iron Man]], [[Spider-Man]], and [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]].<ref name="kotaku">{{Cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5690249/marvel-pinball-from-comics-page-to-silver-ball |title=Marvel Pinball: From Comics Page To Silver Ball |first=Mike |last=Fahey |date=2010-11-15 |accessdate=2010-11-30 |publisher=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref>  Achievements are based on the table rather than the game, allowing ''Pinball FX 2'' to have a record 2050 [[Xbox Live#Gamerscore|gamerscore]] and 97 [[Achievement (video gaming)|achievements]] on Xbox Live Arcade.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.avault.com/news/pinball-fx-2-questions-answered/ |title=Pinball FX 2 questions answered |first=Michele |last=White |publisher=Adrenaline Vault |date=2010-09-22 |accessdate=2010-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/63262/Pinball_FX_2__Your_Questions_Answered__BioLabRevealed.php |title=Pinball FX 2 - Your Questions Answered & BioLab Revealed |publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=2010-11-30 |date=2010-09-22}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The number of achievements and gamerscore has since been increased with additional table releases.|group="note"}} Each table can also be tweaked and configured via the game's Operators menu. This allows players to adjust where certain parts of the table are located and how many points unlock special sections and features of the table.<ref name="gamezone review" /> On April 20, 2011, the Mars table was released. Themed around the [[Mars|planet]] of the same name, it is the first new individual table since the release of ''Pinball FX 2''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://marketplace.xbox.com/en-US/Product/Mars-Full/8f0c05d3-7d9e-4db4-8bef-c2b6e6ed34ba |publisher=[[xbox.com]] |title=Mars (Full) |accessdate=2011-04-27}}</ref> On August 31, 2011, ''Pinball FX 2'' received its first original individual table with the release of ''[[Ms. Splosion Man]]'', a table based on the Xbox Live Arcade platformer of the same name developed by [[Twisted Pixel Games]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5833831/fx-pinball-ms-splosion-man-table?tag=pinballfx2 |date=2011-08-24 |accessdate=2011-09-30 |publisher=Kotaku |first=Owen |last=Good |title=Ms. 'Splosion Man Crosses Over With Pinball FX 2 Next Week}}</ref> From October 26 to November 2, 2011, the full version of the Paranormal table was given away for free as a gift to the game's fans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swilinski|first=Alexander|title=Pinball FX2 offers free 'Paranormal' table starting next Wednesday|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/10/19/pinball-fx2-offers-free-paranormal-table-starting-next-wednesd/|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=19 February 2012|date=2011-10-19}}</ref> On September 4, 2012, a table based on the popular [[PopCap Games]] title ''[[Plants vs. Zombies]]'' was released for both ''Pinball FX 2'' and the newly released ''[[Zen Pinball 2]]'' for the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation Vita]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/08/31/plants-vs-zombies-shambling-to-zen-pinball-2-and-pinball-fx2-next-week/|title=Plants vs. Zombies shambling to Zen Pinball 2 and Pinball FX2 next week|first=Sam|last=Barsanti|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=2012-08-31 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> On December 12, 2012, four tables from ''[[Zen Pinball]]'' were released for ''Pinball FX 2'', leaving only one PlayStation 3-exclusive table from the original ''Zen Pinball'' remaining on that platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/12/10/zen-classics-dlc-flippers-over-to-xblas-pinball-fx2-this-wedn/|title='Zen Classics' DLC flippers over to XBLA's Pinball FX2 this Wednesday|first=Alexander|last=Sliwinski|publisher=[[Joystiq]]|date=2012-12-10|accessdate=2012-12-12}}</ref> Said last table, a table based on ''[[Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2]]'', was finally released on the Xbox One version on December 4, 2014,<ref name="ngs2">{{cite web|last=Teuscher|first=Zac|title=Ninja Gaiden Sigma 2 table released for Pinball FX2 on Xbox One|url=http://www.xblafans.com/ninja-gaiden-sigma-2-table-released-for-pinball-fx2-on-xbox-one-77784.html|publisher=XBLA Fans|accessdate=28 February 2015|date=4 December 2014}}</ref> thus removing all table exclusivity for ''Zen Pinball''.

