==Development and marketing==
''Pinball FX 2''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> existence was first leaked to the public via the [[Australian Classification Board]] website on August 11, 2010.<ref name="leak">{{Cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/08/11/pinball-fx-2-exposed-by-australian-ratings-office/ |title=Pinball FX 2 exposed by Australian ratings office |first=Randy |last=Nelson |date=2010-08-11 |accessdate=2010-11-29 |publisher=Joystiq}}</ref>  It was officially announced on August 31, 2010.<ref name="announced">{{Cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5626415/pinball-fx-2-is-xbox-lives-pinball-platform |title=Pinball FX 2 Is Xbox Live's Pinball Platform |first=Mike |last=Fahey |date=2010-08-31 |accessdate=2010-11-29 |publisher=Kotaku}}</ref>  The game was originally slated for release on October 13, 2010, however last minute delays pushed the game back two weeks.<ref name="delay">{{Cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/10/12/pinball-fx-2-delayed-still-part-of-xblas-game-feast/ |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=2010-11-29 |title=Pinball FX 2 delayed, still part of XBLA's Game Feast |first=Griffin |last=McElroy |date=2010-10-12}}</ref>  It was released for the [[Xbox 360]] via the [[Xbox Live Arcade]] Marketplace on October 27, 2010 as part of [[Microsoft]]'s Game Feast promotion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/30226/Super_Meat_Boy_Main_Course_For_New_Game_Feast_Fall_XBLA_Promo.php |publisher=Gamasutra |date=2010-09-02 |accessdate=2010-10-12 |title=Super Meat Boy 'Main Course' For New Game Feast Fall XBLA Promo |first=Leigh |last=Alexander}}</ref>  The development team consisted of roughly 15 individuals, and development lasted 18 months.<ref name="xblaratings interview">{{Cite web |url=http://www.xblaratings.com/developer-qaa/3264-pinball-fx-2-developer-interview |title=Pinball FX 2 Developer Interview |date=2010-10-27 |accessdate=2010-11-29 |publisher=xblaratings.com}}</ref>

Zen Studios [[Managing Director]] Zsolt Kigyossy detailed the reasons for focusing primarily on pinball games.  "We have guys in the studio who have spent countless hours and pockets full of money at arcades playing pinball."<ref name="gamesworld interview">{{Cite web |url=http://gamesworld.blox.pl/2011/02/Designing-in-unconventional-ways-an-interview.html |title=Designing in unconventional ways - an interview with ZEN Studios |accessdate=2011-02-03 |date=2011-02-03 |publisher=gamesworld.blox.pl |quote=We already know that new tables for Marvel Pinball will be available, such as the Captain America table.}}</ref>  Kigyossy explained that the design process for the tables begins with a conceptual design on paper.  Basic 3D models and shapes are then created and implemented into a test environment.  The artists then add graphical details and animations.  Once gameplay and visual design is complete a final pass is made "properly lighting the table, so the tables becomes lifelike."<ref name="gamesworld interview" />  Simultaneously other designers work on the LED display system, sound and gameplay mechanics.  The game then spends two to three months in testing before the table is considered ready for release.  The entire process takes approximately six months per table.<ref name="gamesworld interview" />  Kigyossy further stated the team plans to "keep the tables coming, support our games long term, and give fans a great selection to choose from."<ref name="gamesworld interview" />

The developers stated that they listened to fan responses from the first game and implemented those ideas into the sequel.  "We have been listening to our fans and building the pinball game that they envisioned," stated Kigyossy. "It took a little longer than expected, but we have designed a game that unifies the online community, and takes all the social features to the next level."<ref name="announced" />  The game was made available free of charge and gives players the ability to try any table for a limited time.  Players can then elect to download ''Pinball FX 2 Core'' which unlocks full versions of the ''Pinball FX 2'' tables.  Owners of the original ''Pinball FX'' can import their existing tables, then selectively choose which of the new tables they want to download.<ref name="announced" />  Players who do not own ''Pinball FX'' can purchase the ''Pinball FX Classic'' pack, which contains the three original tables along with the free downloadable table from the original game.<ref name="announced" />  Kigyossy hinted that some of the exclusive tables from ''[[Zen Pinball]]'' would be coming in the future to ''Pinball FX 2'',<ref name="gamesworld interview" /> which was realized when the Mars table was released on April 20, 2011.<ref name="mars">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamershell.com/news_115692.html |title=Mars table live now for Pinball FX2 |publisher=[[Gamers Hell]] |date=April 21, 2011 |accessdate=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Zen Studios announced on February 29, 2012 that the game would be available for free along with the Sorcerer's Lair table for [[Windows 8]] users, with the additional tables available as premium downloadable content.<ref name="windows 8">{{Cite web |url=http://www.strategyinformer.com/news/16824/pinball-fx-2-a-free-download-for-windows-8-consumer-preview |title=Pinball FX 2 a free download for Windows 8 Consumer Preview |date=2012-02-29 |first=Jonah |last=Falcon |publisher=Strategy Informer |accessdate=2012-02-29}}</ref> It was released on the new OS for download from the [[Windows Store]] on October 27, 2012, although the Mars table was provided for free instead.<ref name="win8" />

A port of ''Pinball FX 2'' to [[Xbox One]] was announced in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/2014/03/17/pinball-fx2-also-announced-for-xbox-one|title=Pinball FX2 also announced for Xbox One|author=Matt Liebl|work=gamezone.com|date=March 17, 2014|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Zen Studios set a launch date for July 31, 2014 and further announced that the front-end would be free to download and include ''Sorcerer's Lair'', with the game running in 1080p and at 60 frames per second.<ref name="IGN-Launch">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/07/16/pinball-fx-2-heading-to-xbox-one-this-month|title=Pinball FX 2 Heading to Xbox One This Month|author=Evan Campbell|work=ign.com|publisher=Ziff-Davis|date=July 16, 2014|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> The announcement also noted that owners of the Xbox 360 edition of the game would have to repurchase Xbox One versions of tables they already owned on Xbox 360.<ref name="IGN-Launch"/> Later that month, however, Zen Studios announced a delay of the release of ''Pinball FX 2'' into August 2014, but added the delay was necessary in order to update the game to permit players to transfer their tables from Xbox 360 to Xbox One at no additional charge.<ref name="IGN-Delay">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/07/30/pinball-fx-2-tables-will-transfer-to-xbox-one-after-all|title=Pinball FX 2 Tables Will Transfer to Xbox One After All|author=Evan Campbell|work=ign.com|publisher=Ziff-Davis|date=July 30, 2014|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> On August 14, 2014, Zen Studios announced that ''Pinball FX 2'' was officially available for Xbox One, including the ability to import tables from the Xbox 360 version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailygame.net/videogames/xbox-one/pinball-fx2-xbox-one-now-live-delay|title=Pinball FX2 Xbox One Now Live After Delay|author=Jonas Allen|work=dailygame.net|date=August 14, 2014|accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, the Windows 8 version of the game was updated with a new pane-based UI and the ability to play all available tables in the game for free with video advertisements playing before each game.<ref name="Win8 update">{{cite web|url=http://forum.zenstudios.com/showthread.php?6631-Windows-8-Update-Issue-Table-Issues|title=Windows 8 update|publisher=Zen Studios forums|accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Except for ''Star Wars Pinball'' tables, which still require full table purchases to play.|group="note"}} The option to buy full tables were maintained, as buying full tables in the new Windows 8 version removes the adverts and allows access to the tables' operator's menu feature.<ref name="Win8 update" /> However, the update was plagued with issues, including some of the tables being (initially) removed post-update and problems of restoring the full ad-free versions of tables if they were purchased pre-update, including the restoration of the then-fully free Mars table.<ref name="Win8 update" />

''Pinball FX2 VR'', a version of the game that supports [[virtual reality]] headset the [[Oculus Rift]], is expected to be released on March 28, 2016. The VR-enabled version will initially include three tables (Mars, Secrets of the Deep, and Epic Quest), placing these tables in a virtual beach-side house.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-03-10-pinball-fx2-vr-slated-for-oculus-rift-this-month | title = Pinball FX2 VR is coming to Oculus Rift this month | first = Jeffrey | last= Matulef | date = March 10, 2016 | accessdate = March 10, 2016 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>

==Reception==
{{Video game reviews
| title = Pinball FX 2
| GR = 84.29%<ref name="gamerankings" />
| MC = 88/100<ref name="metacritic" />
| EuroG = 9/10<ref name="eurogamer review" />
| GI = 9/10<ref name="gameinformer review" />
| GSpot = 8.5/10<ref name="gamespot review" />
| OXM = 8.5/10<ref>"Official Xbox Magazine" (Nov 2010)</ref>
| TX = 9.3/10
}}

''Pinball FX 2'' received positive reviews from critics.  On the aggregate sites [[GameRankings]] and [[Metacritic]], it holds a score of 84.29% and 88/100, respectively.<ref name="gamerankings">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xbox360/605501-pinball-fx-2/index.html |title=Pinball FX 2 for Xbox 360 - GameRankings |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref><ref name="metacritic">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/pinball-fx-2/critic-reviews |title=Pinball FX 2 for Xbox 360 Reviews, Ratings, Credits and More at Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref>  Both sites report a majority review scores of 80% and higher.<ref name="gamerankings2">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xbox360/605501-pinball-fx-2/articles.html?sort=6 |title=Pinball FX 2 Reviews and Articles for Xbox 360 - GameRankings |publisher=GameRankings |accessdate=2010-08-30}}</ref><ref name="metacritic2">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/pinball-fx-2/critic-reviews |title=Pinball FX 2 Critic Reviews for Xbox 360 at metacritic.com |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=2010-08-30}}</ref>  Sales were high its first week of release, moving over 19,000 units.<ref name="gamasutra sales October">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/31658/InDepth_Xbox_Live_Arcade_Sales_Analysis_October_2010.php |title=In-Depth: Xbox Live Arcade Sales Analysis, October 2010 |first=Ryan |last=Langley |publisher=Gamasutra |date=2010-11-23 |accessdate=2010-11-23}}</ref>  2010 sales have exceeded 82,000 units for the Core pack.  Individual downloadable table sales have ranged from 47,000 to 97,000 units.<ref name="gamerbytes 2010 sales">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamerbytes.com/2011/01/indepth_xbox_live_arcade_sales_18.php#more |title=XBLA: In-Depth: Xbox Live Arcade Sales Analysis For All Of 2010 |first=Ryan |last=Langley |publisher=Gamerbytes |date=2011-01-28 |accessdate=2011-01-31}}</ref>  Reviewers felt the game was an improvement over its predecessor, ''Pinball FX''. [[GamesRadar]]'s Matthew Keast stated "You'll forget you're not playing an actual table."<ref name="gamesradar review">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/xbox360/pinball-fx-2/review/pinball-fx-2-review/a-20101029132126468045/g-2010083112345887099 |title=Pinball FX 2 |first=Matthew |last=Keast |accessdate=2010-11-30 |date=2010-10-29 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]]}}</ref>  Nick Chester of Destructoid added "Zen [Studios] already has pinball on consoles nailed."<ref name="destructoid review" />

Critics praised the game's ability to play updated versions of the tables previously available for ''Pinball FX''.  Andrew Reiner of ''[[Game Informer]]'' expressed satisfaction with the functionality, indicating that the new social scoring mechanics provided incentive to play the tables again in the new engine.<ref name="gameinformer review">{{Cite web |url=http://gameinformer.com/games/pinball_fx_2/b/xbox360/archive/2010/11/01/a-surprisingly-addictive-social-experience.aspx |accessdate=2010-11-29 |publisher=''[[Game Informer]]'' |title=Pinball FX 2 |date=2010-11-01 |first=Andrew |last=Reiner}}</ref> [[Eurogamer]]'s Kristan Reed noted that all of the tables from both games are available for demo play.<ref name="eurogamer review">{{Cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-29-download-games-roundup-review |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=2010-11-29 |date=2010-10-29 |title=Download Games Roundup |first=Kristan |last=Reed}}</ref>  Several reviewers also praised the upgraded physics, feeling that they were lifelike.<ref name="gamezone review" /><ref name="gamesradar review" />  Richard Basset of [[TeamXbox]] noted that the game's graphics were a vast improvement, noting that tables from ''Pinball FX'' also received visual upgrades.<ref name="teamxbox review">{{Cite web |url=http://reviews.teamxbox.com/xbox-360/1885/Pinball-FX-2/p1/ |title=Pinball FX 2 Review (Xbox 360) |first=Richard |last=Bassett |date=2010-10-29 |publisher=[[TeamXbox]] |accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref>  Table design itself was also given high marks, with Reed calling them "excellent".<ref name="eurogamer review" /> [[GameSpot]]'s Justin Calvert noted the wide variety of tables, but expressed frustration regarding the purchasing of new tables.  "It's unfortunate that not all of the tables are available to buy individually" stated Calvert, adding "you have to buy at least one of the four-packs before you have the option to play any of the singles."<ref name="gamespot review">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/puzzle/pinballfx2/review.html |accessdate=2010-11-29 |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |title=Pinball FX 2 Review |first=Justin |last=Calvert |date=2010-11-04}}</ref>

The game's updated multiplayer and other new features also received high marks.  TeamXbox's Richard Basset praised the addition of split-screen multiplayer, as did GameSpot's Justin Calvert.<ref name="gamespot review" /><ref name="teamxbox review" />  Calvert also noted the addition of four player, turn-based local multiplayer was a welcome addition.<ref name="gamespot review" />  Kristan Reed of Eurogamer noted the new ability to adjust settings on the tables, allowing for enthusiasts to tweak the game to their liking.  He also lauded the new social features, calling them the "real genius" of the game.<ref name="eurogamer review" />  Some reviewers mentioned that while the online multiplayer was impressive they had difficulty finding games to join.<ref name="gamesradar review" />
