{{Infobox museum | name = The Ice Aquarium | native_name = 氷の水族館 | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = Frozen fish in ice1.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = Exhibit at The Ice Museum | map_type = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|38|54|0.3|N|141|34|46.3|E|region:JP-04_type:landmark|display=inline, title}} | former_name = | established = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[Kesennuma, Miyagi]], Japan | type = | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = | executive_director = | leader_type = | leader = | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | embedded = }} The {{Nihongo|'''Ice Aquarium'''|氷の水族館|Kōri no Suizokukan}} is a tourist attraction in the north-eastern port of [[Kesennuma, Miyagi]], Japan, operated by the Okamoto Ice Refrigeration Plant.<ref name=Hornyak>Hornyak, Tim. [http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-20014321-1.html "Marine life frozen in time at Japan's Ice Aquarium".] ''[[CNET|cnet asia]]'', August 23, 2010</ref> It features approximately 450 marine creatures that were [[Flash freezing|flash-frozen]] into blocks of ice after being caught by local fishermen.<ref name=Smith>Smith, Rachel. [http://www.rdasia.com/in-this-issue?trkid=RDissueblock "The World's Weirdest Tourist Attractions",] ''[[Reader's Digest Association|Reader's Digest Asia]]'', February 2012.</ref> The attraction was established in 2002.<ref>BuzzFeed, [https://www.buzzfeed.com/melismashable/the-japanese-ice-aquarium "The Japanese Ice Aquarium",] ''BuzzFeed, Inc'', 12 July 2011</ref> It showcases more than 70 different species of [[sea creatures]], including [[crab]], [[squid]] and [[octopus]],<ref name=Heimbuch>Heimbuch, Jaymi. [http://www.treehugger.com/green-food/japans-ice-aquarium-displays-fish-frozen-in-mid-swim.html "Japan's Ice Aquarium Displays Fish Frozen In Mid-Swim".] ''Treehugger by [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]]'', August 24, 2010</ref> Due to the extreme cold temperature inside the Ice Aquarium, visitors are advised to stay for only five minutes.
